         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility"> ¶ These plants are peculiarly interesting for the record of the locality which accompanies them. A new saltbush I named in honour of yourself  ¶ Bassia Cornishiana ¶ . ¶  Do you think that any settle...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">85.09.00a</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To William Cornish</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Letter not found. The text given here is from 'New Australian plants', <seg style="font-style: italic; ">South Australian register</seg>, 18 September 1885, p. 5 (B85.09.03). The extract is introduced by the following remarks: 'A few weeks ago, when Mr. Cornish, of the Survey Department, returned from his trip into the far interior of the colony, he sent to Baron von Mueller, of Melbourne, a number of curious plants obtained in Central Australia. He has received in reply a courteous letter of acknowledgment, in which the learned botanist says:—'.</p>
               </note>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>These plants are peculiarly interesting for the record of the locality which accompanies them. A new saltbush I named in honour of yourself <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                  <name key="Bassia%20Cornishiana">Bassia Cornishiana</name>
               </seg>.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M described <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Bassia%20Cornishiana">Bassia Cornishiana</name>
                     </seg> in B85.09.01, p. 41.</p>
               </note> Do you think that any settlers on the boundary line between South Australia and Queensland could be induced to try<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The versions in B85.09.06 and B85.09.07 have 'dry'.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> plants for me near their places of abode? In that case I will write to them.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See also M to W. Cornish, October 1885 (in this edition as <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>85-10-00b).</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Bassia%20Cornishiana">Bassia Cornishiana</name>
            </p>
